Five Truths About Terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is hostage to terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or about 16% of the population, now listed terrorism as the top issue facing the country – an increase of 3% in a month.
For ten years, never have so many Americans been so concerned about terrorism, even though their number is still very much lower than the 46% recorded the day after the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion have primarily been felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
Donald Trump's candidacy, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not incendiary), undoubtedly benefited from it.
Some politicians are allowed to refer to the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But candidates for the presidential election, just like some media outlets, who adhere to the old saying "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated the situation.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
The terrorists are more concerned with holding the spotlight and dominating the political headlines than with the number, in itself, of their victims.
The Islamic State (ISIS) takes great care with its staging.
The barbaric decapitations broadcasted on social networks are intended to destabilize and shock – and therefore to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating the consequences and making headlines with every terrorist act is playing into the terrorists' hands.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat facing populations in developed countries.
Terrorism kills far less than road accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than to be killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen is killed by a terrorist, according to experts, is one in 3.5 million.
Americans are at greater risk of dying in their bathtub (a probability of 1 in 950,000), from a domestic appliance accident (a probability of 1 in 1.5 million), from a deer or moose crossing the road (a probability of 1 in 2 million), or in a commercial airplane crash (a probability of 1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year in car accidents while texting or talking on their cell phones.
It is several hundred times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings on campuses or in schools.
Terrorism is not the Third World War.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a terrorist surge.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of state leaders in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, originating from the "autonomous" left, diverted airplanes outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's extremist jihadists are an old political phenomenon dressed in religious clothing.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identities have been shattered by globalization, seeking meaning in the imagined and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to overcome them, but the restrictive nature of EI limits its area of attraction.
His sectarian attacks already prevent him from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
The ISIS will ultimately be defeated, just as previous transnational terrorist groups have been.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weaker of the two opponents uses the strength of the stronger one to defeat him.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have managed to overthrow one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking enough citizens of a state to push them into futile actions, they may hope to gain an advantage.
In 2001, Al-Qaida managed to lure the Americans into Afghanistan.
ISIS was born from the ashes of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, one needs smart power.
An intelligent power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the military and police with the influence power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
Power and influence are also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery and prevent those who are unredeemable from recruiting.
This is why the attention given to the narrative of events and the way U.S. actions are commented on social media is as important and necessary as precision air strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
This is why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of the reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Let us not fill the theater where actions carried out by brutes and hoodlums take place.
If we hand over the great stage of our public speech to them, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and reveal our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
